---
import Docs from '../../layouts/Docs.astro';
import CopyCommand from '../../components/CopyCommand.astro';
import Code from '../../components/Code.astro';
import { href } from '../../lib/site';
---

<Docs
  title="Browser & focus"
  eyebrow="Documentation · Reference"
  summary="A quiet, hardened browser, encrypted DNS, and a distraction blocklist you own — for people who are serious about getting work done."
>
  <p>
    Attention is the scarce resource. Ubuntu Candor treats it that way: the
    browser ships hardened and silent, DNS leaves the machine encrypted, and a
    small, blunt blocklist keeps the classic time-sinks one keystroke from gone.
    All of it is plain configuration you can read and tune.
  </p>

  <h2 id="firefox">Firefox defaults</h2>
  <p>
    The <code>firefox</code> step installs an enterprise policy at
    <code>/etc/firefox/policies/policies.json</code>. It applies to every
    profile on the next launch — no clicking through settings:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No telemetry or studies.</strong> Usage data and Mozilla experiments are off.</li>
    <li><strong>No noise on the new tab.</strong> Sponsored tiles, Pocket, and snippets are gone.</li>
    <li><strong>No onboarding or "what's new".</strong> Feature nags and recommendation prompts are disabled.</li>
    <li><strong>No first-run or post-update pages.</strong> You open the browser, you get to work.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    None of this is locked — it's a baseline. Edit
    <code>setup/firefox/policies.json</code> and re-run to change any of it.
    Every key is documented in
    <a href="https://mozilla.github.io/policy-templates/">Mozilla's policy templates</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="ublock">uBlock Origin</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://github.com/gorhill/uBlock">uBlock Origin</a> is
    force-installed through the same policy, so it's present and enabled on
    first launch — nothing to install by hand:
  </p>
  <Code caption="setup/firefox/policies.json">
    <span class="tok-comment">"ExtensionSettings"</span>: {'{'}
      <span class="tok-comment">"uBlock0@raymondhill.net"</span>: {'{'}
        <span class="tok-comment">"installation_mode"</span>: <span class="tok-flag">"force_installed"</span>,
        <span class="tok-comment">"install_url"</span>: <span class="tok-flag">"https://addons.mozilla.org/…/ublock-origin/latest.xpi"</span>
      {'}'}
    {'}'}
  </Code>
  <p>
    Its default filter lists handle ads and trackers. The distraction blocklist
    below is layered on top as your own rules.
  </p>

  <h2 id="dns">Encrypted DNS</h2>
  <p>
    The <code>dns</code> step points <code>systemd-resolved</code> at
    <a href="https://quad9.net">Quad9</a> over TLS, so every lookup on the
    machine — not just the browser's — is encrypted in transit and filtered for
    known-malicious domains:
  </p>
  <Code caption="/etc/systemd/resolved.conf.d/10-candor-dns.conf">
    [Resolve]
    DNS=9.9.9.9#dns.quad9.net
    DNSOverTLS=yes
  </Code>
  <p>
    Firefox's own DNS-over-HTTPS is deliberately turned <em>off</em> in the
    policy, so the browser defers to this system resolver instead of quietly
    sending your lookups somewhere else. Prefer a different provider? Change the
    <code>DNS=</code> line — Cloudflare, Mullvad, and NextDNS all work.
  </p>

  <h2 id="blocklist">The distraction blocklist</h2>
  <p>
    This is the heart of the focus setup, and it's intentionally simple. The
    blocklist is a plain text file — one domain per line:
  </p>
  <Code caption="setup/blocklist.txt">
    <span class="tok-comment"># social / infinite scroll</span>
    facebook.com
    instagram.com
    x.com
    tiktok.com

    <span class="tok-comment"># forums / aggregators</span>
    reddit.com
    <span class="tok-comment"># news.ycombinator.com        ← commented out = not blocked</span>
  </Code>

  <h3 id="how-it-works">How it works</h3>
  <p>
    At install, the <code>firefox</code> step turns each line into a uBlock
    static filter — <code>facebook.com</code> becomes
    <code>||facebook.com^</code> — and writes them into uBlock's managed
    settings inside the Firefox policy. uBlock reads them as your user filters
    on launch. There's no background service and no separate app: the file is
    the source of truth, and the browser enforces it.
  </p>
  <Code>
    <span class="tok-comment"># setup/blocklist.txt  →  compiled into the policy</span>
    facebook.com   →   <span class="tok-flag">||facebook.com^</span>
    x.com          →   <span class="tok-flag">||x.com^</span>
  </Code>

  <h3 id="tuning">Tuning it</h3>
  <p>
    The list is deliberately small — comprehensive enough to matter, short
    enough to read in one sitting. It's a starting point, not a verdict:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Need a site for work?</strong> Comment it out with <code>#</code> or delete the line.</li>
    <li><strong>Want more blocked?</strong> Add domains, one per line.</li>
    <li><strong>Just this once?</strong> Toggle a rule in the uBlock dashboard for a single session without touching the file.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Apply your changes by re-running the one step:</p>
  <div class="not-prose my-6">
    <CopyCommand command="./setup/bootstrap.sh --only firefox" />
  </div>

  <p>
    Because the file lives in the repo, your focus policy versions and travels
    with the rest of your setup — see
    <a href={href('/docs/customizing/')}>Customizing</a>.
  </p>
</Docs>
